onBeforeRequest.name: onBeforeRequest
onBeforeRequest.comment: Fired when a request is about to occur.

onBeforeSendHeaders.name: onBeforeSendHeaders
onBeforeSendHeaders.comment: Fired before sending an HTTP request, once the request headers are available. This may occur after a TCP connection is made to the server, but before any HTTP data is sent.

onSendHeaders.name: onSendHeaders
onSendHeaders.comment: Fired just before a request is going to be sent to the server (modifications of previous onBeforeSendHeaders callbacks are visible by the time onSendHeaders is fired).

onHeadersReceived.name: onHeadersReceived
onHeadersReceived.comment: Fired when HTTP response headers of a request have been received.

onAuthRequired.name: onAuthRequired
onAuthRequired.comment: Fired when an authentication failure is received. The listener has three options: it can provide authentication credentials, it can cancel the request and display the error page, or it can take no action on the challenge. If bad user credentials are provided, this may be called multiple times for the same request.

onResponseStarted.name: onResponseStarted
onResponseStarted.comment: Fired when the first byte of the response body is received. For HTTP requests, this means that the status line and response headers are available.

onBeforeRedirect.name: onBeforeRedirect
onBeforeRedirect.comment: Fired when a server-initiated redirect is about to occur.

available.name: available
available.comment:
Returns true if the API is available. The common causes of an API not being avilable are:

  • a permission is missing in the application's manifest.json file
  • the API is defined on a newer version of Chrome then the current runtime

MAX_HANDLER_BEHAVIOR_CHANGED_CALLS_PER_1.name: MAX_HANDLER_BEHAVIOR_CHANGED_CALLS_PER_10_MINUTES
MAX_HANDLER_BEHAVIOR_CHANGED_CALLS_PER_1.comment: The maximum number of times that handlerBehaviorChanged can be called per 10 minute sustained interval. handlerBehaviorChanged is an expensive function call that shouldn't be called often.

handlerBehaviorChanged.name: handlerBehaviorChanged
handlerBehaviorChanged.comment: Needs to be called when the behavior of the webRequest handlers has changed to prevent incorrect handling due to caching. This function call is expensive. Don't call it often.

hashCode.name: hashCode
hashCode.comment:
Get a hash code for this object.

All objects have hash codes. Hash codes are guaranteed to be the same for objects that are equal when compared using the equality operator ==. Other than that there are no guarantees about the hash codes. They will not be consistent between runs and there are no distribution guarantees.

If a subclass overrides chrome/chrome_ext.ChromeWebRequest.hashCode it should override the equality operator as well to maintain consistency.

runtimeType.name: runtimeType
runtimeType.comment: A representation of the runtime type of the object.

available.comment:
Returns true if the API is available. The common causes of an API not being avilable are:

  • a permission is missing in the application's manifest.json file
  • the API is defined on a newer version of Chrome then the current runtime

==.comment:
The equality operator.

The default behavior for all dart-core.Objects is to return true if and only if this and chrome/chrome_ext.ChromeWebRequest.==.other are the same object.

Override this method to specify a different equality relation on a class. The overriding method must still be an equivalence relation. That is, it must be:

  • Total: It must return a boolean for all arguments. It should never throw or return null.

  • Reflexive: For all objects o, o == o must be true.

  • Symmetric: For all objects o1 and o2, o1 == o2 and o2 == o1 must either both be true, or both be false.

  • Transitive: For all objects o1, o2, and o3, if o1 == o2 and o2 == o3 are true, then o1 == o3 must be true.

The method should also be consistent over time, so equality of two objects should not change over time, or at least only change if one of the objects was modified.

If a subclass overrides the equality operator it should override the chrome/chrome_ext.ChromeWebRequest.hashCode method as well to maintain consistency.

toString.name: toString
toString.comment: Returns a string representation of this object.

noSuchMethod.name: noSuchMethod
noSuchMethod.comment:
chrome/chrome_ext.ChromeWebRequest.noSuchMethod is invoked when users invoke a non-existent method on an object. The name of the method and the arguments of the invocation are passed to chrome/chrome_ext.ChromeWebRequest.noSuchMethod in an dart-core.Invocation. If chrome/chrome_ext.ChromeWebRequest.noSuchMethod returns a value, that value becomes the result of the original invocation.

The default behavior of chrome/chrome_ext.ChromeWebRequest.noSuchMethod is to throw a dart-core.NoSuchMethodError.
